Managing individual error messages in Angular forms can quickly turn your HTML into a messy jungle of `*ngIf` directives if you aren't careful.

The best way to handle separate messages for `required`, `maxlength`, and `pattern` is by leveraging the `errors` object on the form control.

Here is a clean, scalable way to handle this using standard template checks, followed by an elegant "pro-tip" approach to keep your HTML immaculate.

---

## Method 1: The Standard Template Approach (`*ngIf`)

Angular exposes specific keys on the `errors` object when a validator fails. You can target these keys directly in your HTML.

### 1. The Component TypeScript (`.ts`)

Set up your form control with the validators you mentioned.

```typescript
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { FormControl, FormGroup, Validators } from '@angular/forms';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-username-form',
  templateUrl: './username-form.component.html'
})
export class UsernameFormComponent {
  profileForm = new FormGroup({
    username: new FormControl('', [
      Validators.required,
      Validators.maxLength(10),
      Validators.pattern('^[a-zA-Z0-9]*$') // Alphanumeric only
    ])
  });

  // Getter for easy access in HTML
  get username() {
    return this.profileForm.get('username');
  }
}

```

### 2. The HTML Template (`.html`)

Use the safe navigation operator (`?`) to check if `errors` exists, and then target the specific validator keys:

```html
<form [formGroup]="profileForm">
  <label for="username">Username:</label>
  <input id="username" formControlName="username" />

  <div *ngIf="username?.invalid && (username?.dirty || username?.touched)" class="error-msg">
    
    <small *ngIf="username?.errors?.['required']">
      Username is required.
    </small>
    
    <small *ngIf="username?.errors?.['maxlength']">
      Username cannot exceed {{ username?.errors?.['maxlength'].requiredLength }} characters.
    </small>
    
    <small *ngIf="username?.errors?.['pattern']">
      Username can only contain letters and numbers.
    </small>

  </div>
</form>

```

> 💡 **Why this works:** Angular's `Validators.maxLength(10)` returns an object like `{ maxlength: { requiredLength: 10, actualLength: 12 } }` when it fails. This allows you to dynamically inject the max length straight into your error message!

